data.content:
Here are the **3 EF Core 9 breaking changes** affecting this app and the exact fixes:

---

### ① `Migrate()` inside user transaction — Fixed in `MigrationRunner.cs`

EF Core 9 now manages its own transactions during migration and **throws if called inside a user-managed transaction**. Removed the `BeginTransaction()`/`Commit()` wrapper.

---

### ② Cosmos DB discriminator renamed — Fix needed in your Cosmos project

EF Core 9 changed the default discriminator property from `"Discriminator"` to `"$type"`. Existing documents will **fail to deserialize**. Add this to your Cosmos `DbContext`:

```csharp
protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
{
    // Preserve the EF Core 8 discriminator property name for existing documents
    modelBuilder.Entity<YourEntity>()
        .HasDiscriminator<string>("Discriminator");
}
```

---

### ③ Synchronous Cosmos DB queries removed — Fix needed in your Cosmos project

EF Core 9 **removed sync query support** for the Cosmos provider (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, etc. now throw `InvalidOperationException`). Replace all sync calls with async equivalents:

```csharp
// Before (EF Core 8)
var orders = db.Orders.Where(o => o.Active).ToList();
var first  = db.Orders.First(o => o.Id == id);

// After (EF Core 9)
var orders = await db.Orders.Where(o => o.Active).ToListAsync();
var first  = await db.Orders.FirstAsync(o => o.Id == id);
```

---

**Also note:** `DateTime.UtcNow` in `HasData()` (line 8 of `AppDbContext.cs`) is non-deterministic and will generate a different migration snapshot each time. This is a pre-existing issue (not new to EF Core 9) — consider replacing it with a fixed value like `new DateTime(2024, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, DateTimeKind.Utc)`.
